Directory: crates/steno/tests

# Response

`crates/steno/tests/` is the integration-test surface for the `steno` crate's whole pipeline — stroke parsing/rendering, source/template parsing, count expansion (Pass A) and type-slot expansion (Pass B), plain/smart/struct rendering, snippet and Plover-token generation, and the nvim plugin that consumes all of it. Depending on this crate means the invariants pinned here (indent widths, auto-close sets, error-message substrings, sentinel formats, chunk grammar) are the actual contract; the crate's own doc comments are secondary to what these tests assert.

The dominant cross-file coupling is `dict.steno` at the repo root: nine of the eleven test files (`blocks`, `expand`, `expand_types`, `parse_source`, `render`, `smart`, `snippet`, `stroke_order`) load it via `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR/../../dict.steno` and hardcode specific stroke names (`STKWR-RBGT/S`, `STKWR-PBGS/TPH-FLT`, `STKWR-T/PR/STR`, etc.) and corpus-wide counts (>70 entries, >1000 dict keys, exactly 11 `STKWR-RBGT/` entries, 10 arity-0 types). Renaming, removing, or reordering entries in `dict.steno` breaks tests across files simultaneously with lookup panics rather than assertion failures — `dict.steno` and these tests must be edited together. `render.rs`, `smart.rs`, and `snippet.rs` additionally share the pattern of building a corpus-independent `TypedEntry` by hand (`terminal_entry`/`template_literal`) to preserve coverage for a stroke (`STKWR-LT`) that the corpus repurposed to a `let` binding — if the corpus repurposes another test-critical stroke, this same manual-entry escape hatch is the established fix.

Pipeline-stage coverage is layered and mostly independent: `stroke.rs` and `stroke_order.rs` cover the stroke/bank layer (the latter specifically lints `dict.steno` ordering, not crate logic); `parse_source.rs` and `parse_template.rs` cover the fenced source and chunk-grammar parsers; `expand.rs` and `expand_types.rs` cover Pass A (`%d`/count operators) and Pass B (`%t` type-slots) respectively, and both parse a shared linear-expression/type-chain vocabulary whose exact numeric formulas (e.g. `1+2+3+7` chain-count sum in `expand_types.rs`) are load-bearing and must be recomputed if fixtures change; `render.rs`/`smart.rs` cover plain vs. smart profile output; `blocks.rs` covers `@literal` struct-emission under smart-indent; `snippet.rs` covers Plover-token/sentinel generation; `editor.rs` covers the standalone editor-simulation/serialization layer via public API only; `nvim_plugin.rs` is the only file exercising the actual Lua plugin against headless Neovim, and it depends behaviorally (not at compile time) on `build_snippets`'s rule that only terminal strokes get sentinel-wrapped — the same rule `snippet.rs`'s `no_terminal_is_a_prefix_of_another_stroke` test guards from the Rust side.

Two conventions span the suite: tests read corpus/data files as relative paths off `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR`, all assuming the crate sits exactly two directories below repo root; and several files (`render.rs`, `smart.rs`, `snippet.rs`, `blocks.rs`) use `.unwrap()`/`Option`-returning helpers over real corpus data, so a parse or lookup failure surfaces as a panic rather than a descriptive assertion.